going to say. Oh, yeah. Well, the players came 
first to me, and I, you know, pick up a buck or two

23:28.091 --> 23:34.038
here. That wasn't so important to me as my 
organization, the players, which I felt and will

23:34.138 --> 23:42.447
feel until the 31st of August is mine. Mm-hmm. 
Well, I think you have every right to feel that way.

23:46.060 --> 23:47.221
You know, it's a strange thing. I used to, not too 
long ago, I'd go out around the country making

23:47.341 --> 24:03.119
little talks to groups of people, and invariably 
I'd be introduced as the voice of Kyle Field. I used

24:04.140 --> 24:05.602
to get a little kick out of that. But the thing is 
this. For just a few hours a year, I perform over

24:13.222 --> 24:14.545
there. Nothing was ever said of the hours and the 
hours and the hours that I spent teaching theater

24:15.207 --> 24:22.985
and doing theater work. You know how little things 
get stuck to you like that? Isn't it funny? That

24:29.500 --> 24:31.264
must be some kind of a... on our society. Well, 
yeah, I suppose, though, it's a few hours a year,

24:35.413 --> 24:39.922
but then... I hit a lot of people. You have a lot of 
thousands of people. Yeah, I hit a lot of people. At

24:45.152 --> 24:48.038
one point, at one time. Over a single football 
season, you probably get as many people hear your

24:48.018 --> 24:59.193
voice as in several years of theater. Well, of 
course, they don't hear your voice at all. Only

25:03.618 --> 25:08.064
those people who are involved in the Aggie 
players, I guess, hear your voice. That's right. I

25:09.719 --> 25:24.501
venture to say probably that any number of those 
people who hear you at the football games are not

25:09.719 --> 25:24.501
even aware of the fact that you are director of the 
Aggie players. They don't know who I am. And it's

25:25.843 --> 25:28.187
well that they don't. After all, the people come to 
see a football game. They come to see the players

25:31.652 --> 25:34.176
play ball. They don't come to hear me. I just happen 
to be an adjunct to the ballgame, that's all.

25:44.146 --> 25:46.851
But you will be continuing in that capacity? I have 
been asked by the athletic department to continue

25:46.871 --> 25:59.892
as the voice of Kyle Field, and I told them I would be 
very happy, the good Lord willing.

26:04.310 --> 26:11.778
How close of a contact with the athletic 
department have you had during your announcing? I

26:11.798 --> 26:21.008
mean, obviously you have to know somewhat more 
about the players than the average spectator who

26:11.798 --> 26:21.008
comes. Well, I go over there on rare occasions. As a 
social visit. And in the next few days, I'm going

26:31.175 --> 26:44.233
over and I'm going to get hold of the defensive 
coach and I'm going to have him show me their

26:31.175 --> 26:44.233
defensive lineups, the various defenses that 
they go into. Then I'm going to get their offensive

26:45.054 --> 26:52.785
lineups, how they run the ball, and I'm going to 
know where these different players are. And

26:54.247 --> 26:55.649
that's about it. That's about it. I don't bother 
them. They don't bother me. In other words, I don't

27:04.802 --> 27:09.327
go there and tell them how to run their football 
club. They love that, I guess. We have very

27:12.612 --> 27:15.595
friendly relationships, very friendly. But as 
you say, people come to see the ballgame, not hear

27:15.615 --> 27:18.799
you. That's right. So your role as the announcer, 
Kyle Field, is considerably different than

27:19.640 --> 27:27.490
the... television broadcast of the game. Oh, yes, 
yes. I work on this theory. The less I say up there,

27:32.119 --> 27:34.809
the better. And I've held that idea for 50 years, 25 
years. Why should I keep saying, well, now this

27:40.210 --> 27:45.922
quarterback is scratching himself. He's under 
the ball. They can see he's under the ball. I don't

27:50.351 --> 27:54.600
have to tell them it's a first down and 15 yards to 
go. They can see that on the scoreboard. I don't

27:57.126 --> 27:58.168
have to tell them. where the ball is on what line it 
is. They can see that. I used to have to when they

28:02.060 --> 28:04.783
didn't have a scoreboard. You know, a fellow way 
down here, and he balled me on the five. I said, the

28:07.646 --> 28:09.328
ball is now on the five. He couldn't see down there. 
He didn't know where it was, even in the field or

28:11.350 --> 28:13.713
not. But they got all that stuff on the board. I 
don't have to tell them that anymore. But they

28:18.558 --> 28:21.962
can't tell who's carrying the ball half the time. 
And they don't, you know, there's a lot of things

28:22.600 --> 28:26.065
they don't see. They don't see a nice block. 
There's one thing about this football that does

28:28.189 --> 28:31.253
bother me a little. You know, the center of the 
offensive team does more work than any other one

28:31.273 --> 28:40.127
man on the ball club. He has to do three things, four 
things. He has to pass the ball to the quarterback

28:43.532 --> 28:47.578
when he's up there hand to hand. He has to pass the 
ball for a place kick, and then he has to pass the

28:47.913 --> 28:52.680
ball for a punt. Now, those are three entirely 
different things. And on every single offensive

28:55.243 --> 29:04.816
play, he has to block somebody, at least one or two 
men.

29:07.640 --> 29:12.507
Now, the other play, you know, you see this fellow 
prancing off here, just floating out there.

29:12.547 --> 29:13.969
Nobody touches him or nothing. He's a decoy, you 
know. But that poor center, that son of a gun is

29:16.583 --> 29:22.155
right in the middle of the hellhole of Calcutta, 
and he catches it every single play. And he's got a

29:28.079 --> 29:29.160
blocker. He does that for defense. He'd get killed 
if he doesn't. He catches it worse when he centers

29:33.345 --> 29:41.115
for the punt or the place kick because he's stirred 
upside down. Yeah, that poof. And you know, you can

29:43.297 --> 29:48.784
seldom mention a fella's name over the PA. You see? 
Very real. The only time he gets mentioned is if he

29:50.182 --> 29:53.253
snaps the ball over somebody's head. No, I won't 
mention that. No, no. Yeah. I don't say you, but in

29:56.444 --> 29:58.431
most... No, I wouldn't. In the print, he would. In 
most... No, I think it was perfect. No, I shouldn't

30:03.560 --> 30:04.922
say that. In those broadcasts or televised... I 
think they talk too much, to tell you the truth. I

30:08.827 --> 30:11.070
really do think they talk too much. Is this perhaps 
a carryover from radio when they were trying to

30:11.090 --> 30:15.115
describe the game? No, I think it's a case of these 
fellows are so in love with their voice and they

30:15.215 --> 30:22.846
love to hear themselves so much they just got to 
keep talking. I shouldn't say that, probably, but

30:23.386 --> 30:26.310
that's the way it appears to me. And I don't know. 
I... Because watching it on TV is different than

30:29.534 --> 30:33.857
being in a stadium.

